  "prompt": "What integer solutions to x and y are there for 167x+113y=1?",
  "response": "Let's solve this step by step using the Euclidean algorithm and B\u00e9zout's identity.\n\n1) First, let's find the GCD of 167 and 113 using the Euclidean algorithm:\n   \u2022 167 = 1 \u00d7 113 + 54\n   \u2022 113 = 2 \u00d7 54 + 5\n   \u2022 54 = 10 \u00d7 5 + 4\n   \u2022 5 = 1 \u00d7 4 + 1\n   \u2022 4 = 4 \u00d7 1 + 0\n\n   So GCD(167, 113) = 1\n\n2) Since the GCD is 1, the equation 167x + 113y = 1 has integer solutions.\n\n3) We can find these solutions using the extended Euclidean algorithm:\n   \u2022 1 = 5 - 1 \u00d7 4\n   \u2022 1 = 5 - 1 \u00d7 (54 - 10 \u00d7 5)\n   \u2022 1 = 11 \u00d7 5 - 1 \u00d7 54\n   \u2022 1 = 11 \u00d7 (113 - 2 \u00d7 54) - 1 \u00d7 54\n   \u2022 1 = 11 \u00d7 113 - 23 \u00d7 54\n   \u2022 1 = 11 \u00d7 113 - 23 \u00d7 (167 - 1 \u00d7 113)\n   \u2022 1 = 34 \u00d7 113 - 23 \u00d7 167\n\n4) So the initial solution is:\n   x = -23\n   y = 34\n\n5) The general solution is given by:\n   x = -23 + 113k\n   y = 34 - 167k\n   where k is any integer\n\nLet's verify the first few solutions:\n\nk = 0: x = -23, y = 34\nk = 1: x = 90, y = -133\nk = -1: x = -136, y = 201\n\nWe can check: \n167(-23) + 113(34) = -3841 + 3842 = 1 \u2713\n167(90) + 113(-133) = 15030 - 15029 = 1 \u2713\n167(-136) + 113(201) = -22712 + 22713 = 1 \u2713\n\nTherefore, the general integer solution is:\nx = -23 + 113k\ny = 34 - 167k\nwhere k is any integer.",
